{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d96ac383-70e7-42a1-a8ad-6c32701b85e8","content":"The template is **technically valid** but has a few gaps I'd address before publishing:\n\n### Missing fields\n| Field | Why it matters |\n|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Enables validation & IntelliSense in editors |\n| `description` | Shown when users run `dotnet new list` — critical for discoverability |\n| `groupIdentity` | Groups related templates in a pack (e.g. across languages/frameworks) |\n| `defaultName` | Controls the fallback project name if the user doesn't specify one |\n\n### What looks good\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author` — all present ✓\n- `tags` with `language` and `type` — correct ✓\n- `sourceName` for namespace replacement — correct ✓\n- `symbols` / framework choice — well-formed ✓\n\n### Recommendation\nAt minimum, add a `description` and `$schema` before publishing:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\",\n  \"description\": \"A template for creating a Web API project.\",\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nConsider adding `groupIdentity` (e.g. `\"MyCompany.WebApi\"`) if you plan to ship multiple related templates in one NuGet package.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9e990ed0-f98f-4195-8085-d445b84a4c2c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nKey fields to check:\n1. `$schema` - Missing. Not required but recommended.\n2. `identity` - Present ✓\n3. `name` - Present ✓\n4. `shortName` - Present ✓\n5. `sourceName` - Present ✓\n6. `author` - Present ✓\n7. `classifications` - Present ✓\n8. `tags` - Present with language and type ✓\n9. `symbols` - Present ✓\n\n\n10. `groupIdentity` - Missing. Recommended for organizing related templates in NuGet, especially when you have multiple language or framework variants.\n11. `precedence` - Missing. Helpful when multiple versions of the same template are installed.\n12. `defaultName` - Missing. Sets the default project name if the user doesn't specify one.\n13. `description` - Missing. This is important for NuGet discoverability since users see this when browsing available templates.\n\nLooking at the official documentation, the truly required fields are just `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, and `author`, which are all present. So the template would technically work, but it's missing some key fields for a polished NuGet release. The `description` field is particularly important for discoverability, and `$schema` would help with validation. The `defaultValue` for Framework is set to \"net9.0\" which is reasonable.","outputTokens":751,"requestId":"C7C0:29F7F6:6A46C19:72A2052:6A03CD6B"},"id":"fef479c5-0efe-49c0-86cf-e3cf6ea8930c","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:01:47.600Z","parentId":"5d1e043b-42d5-47ce-b7f9-fb1c6f82a981"}
